"McElwain J.C., Beerling D.J., Woodward F.I.","Fossil plants and global warming at the Triassic-Jurassic boundary",1999,"Science","285","5432",,"1386","1390",,,10.1126/science.285.5432.1386,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033609999&partnerID=40&md5=9b513c4acb3f794149ce5fc9434f25bf","Dept. of Animal and Plant Sciences, University of Sheffield, Sheffield, S10 2TN, United Kingdom","McElwain, J.C., Dept. of Animal and Plant Sciences, University of Sheffield, Sheffield, S10 2TN, United Kingdom; Beerling, D.J., Dept. of Animal and Plant Sciences, University of Sheffield, Sheffield, S10 2TN, United Kingdom; Woodward, F.I., Dept. of Animal and Plant Sciences, University of Sheffield, Sheffield, S10 2TN, United Kingdom","The Triassic-Jurassic boundary marks a major faunal mass extinction, but records of accompanying environmental changes are limited. Paleobotanical evidence indicates a fourfold increase in atmospheric carbon dioxide concentration and suggests an associated 3°to 4°C 'greenhouse' warming across the boundary. These environmental conditions are calculated to have raised leaf temperatures above a highly conserved lethal limit, perhaps contributing to the >95 percent species-level turnover of Triassic-Jurassic: megaflora.",,"carbon dioxide; flora; global warming; Jurassic; mass extinction; paleoclimate; Triassic; vegetation; article; botany; carbon dioxide measurement; environmental monitoring; fossil; greenhouse effect; priority journal; turnover time",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4",,,,"Raup, D.M., Sepkoski, J.J., (1982) Science, 215, p. 1501; Olsen, P.E., Shubin, N.H., Anders, M.H., (1987) Science, 237, p. 1025; Colbert, E.H., (1986) Dynamics of Extinction, pp. 49-62. , D. K. Elliot, Ed. Wiley, New York; Benton, M.J., (1995) Science, 268, p. 52; Harris, T.M., (1937) Medd. Groen., 112, p. 1; Lundblad, A.B., (1959) K. Sven. Vetenskapsakad. Handl., 6, p. 1; Visscher, H., Brugman, W.A., (1981) Rev. Palaeobot. Palynol., 34, p. 115; Fowel